1
00:00:06,286 --> 00:00:08,487
Good afternoon, everybody. Welcome to my talk.

2
00:00:08,547 --> 00:00:10,648
I'm Toby Hines. I'm the lead character artist

3
00:00:10,748 --> 00:00:11,989
at Sony London Studio.

4
00:00:13,069 --> 00:00:15,370
Just before we get going, I just need to remind you

5
00:00:15,430 --> 00:00:17,291
that you'll get an email about a quarter of an hour

6
00:00:17,331 --> 00:00:20,193
after this talk, and if you could give any feedback,

7
00:00:20,513 --> 00:00:21,553
that would be absolutely brilliant.

8
00:00:22,254 --> 00:00:23,054
Okay, let's get going.

9
00:00:23,954 --> 00:00:25,675
So, this talk is on the development of the characters

10
00:00:25,695 --> 00:00:26,456
for Blood & Truth.

11
00:00:27,036 --> 00:00:29,717
This is the new action shooter for PlayStation VR.

12
00:00:32,162 --> 00:00:34,663
Bluntruth has been developed by Sony London Studio.

13
00:00:35,003 --> 00:00:37,845
Our primary goal is to make groundbreaking VR games.

14
00:00:39,406 --> 00:00:41,627
We released VR Worlds in August 2016.

15
00:00:42,587 --> 00:00:44,569
This was conceived as a set of experiences

16
00:00:44,609 --> 00:00:46,610
to introduce players to PlayStation VR.

17
00:00:47,670 --> 00:00:48,731
Anybody played VR Worlds?

18
00:00:51,232 --> 00:00:51,572
Good.

19
00:00:51,833 --> 00:00:53,313
And did you play the London Heist?

20
00:00:55,074 --> 00:00:55,435
Excellent.

21
00:01:00,849 --> 00:01:03,791
The London Heist was by far the most popular of these games.

22
00:01:03,931 --> 00:01:07,333
We were able to analyze data in the months after we released VR Worlds,

23
00:01:08,094 --> 00:01:11,336
and it was twice as popular as the next most popular experience.

24
00:01:12,517 --> 00:01:15,419
Now this might have been down to just people enjoying shooting things in VR,

25
00:01:16,159 --> 00:01:19,682
but the feedback we got from playtests, reviews, social media and forums

26
00:01:19,822 --> 00:01:24,585
told us that players found the character interactions really immersive and fun.

27
00:01:25,837 --> 00:01:29,939
As you can see from this selection of quotes, the experience of having characters stood

28
00:01:29,979 --> 00:01:33,541
before you in VR and interacting with them is very powerful.

29
00:01:34,842 --> 00:01:37,984
Simple things like a character handing you a cell phone and being able to take it out

30
00:01:38,024 --> 00:01:43,547
of their hands have real impact in VR because you're in the same virtual world as them and

31
00:01:43,567 --> 00:01:45,228
you're physically performing these tasks.

32
00:01:46,529 --> 00:01:49,831
So to take these learnings from the London Heist and have them form the pillars.

33
00:01:50,724 --> 00:01:53,745
of our next game became the main driving force behind Blood and Truth.

34
00:01:53,985 --> 00:01:58,066
How far could we push the envelope on character interaction and player immersion?

35
00:02:01,166 --> 00:02:04,787
This generation of VR is still finding out what works and what doesn't work.

36
00:02:05,307 --> 00:02:08,288
But there are already a lot of rules and commandments about what you should and shouldn't do

37
00:02:08,308 --> 00:02:10,189
that have been put forward by various people.

38
00:02:10,949 --> 00:02:13,789
Two of the big ones relating to characters have traditionally been

39
00:02:14,169 --> 00:02:16,710
realistic characters don't translate well in VR

40
00:02:17,330 --> 00:02:20,391
and players don't like their avatar to depict someone else.

41
00:02:23,250 --> 00:02:24,711
Let's start with realistic characters.

42
00:02:25,331 --> 00:02:32,136
The consensus being, making believable characters risks straying into uncanny valley, unsettling

43
00:02:32,176 --> 00:02:34,357
players and ruining the immersive experience.

44
00:02:36,279 --> 00:02:39,601
To avoid this for the London heist, we had stylized characters.

45
00:02:41,778 --> 00:02:45,821
Now that worked for that tone of experience which was larger than life and over the top,

46
00:02:46,161 --> 00:02:48,283
but we didn't want that style to become set in stone.

47
00:02:48,903 --> 00:02:53,086
And once we'd finished VR Worlds, we knew we wanted a grittier, more serious tone for

48
00:02:53,106 --> 00:02:53,866
the next project.

49
00:02:54,507 --> 00:02:57,009
So we were keen to investigate more realistic characters.

50
00:02:57,309 --> 00:03:00,691
We felt they could work in VR, we just needed the right conditions.

51
00:03:03,233 --> 00:03:06,055
And making highly realistic game characters is very subjective.

52
00:03:07,445 --> 00:03:09,686
People are hardwired to judge virtual humans

53
00:03:09,886 --> 00:03:12,067
with every ounce of scrutiny evolution has given us.

54
00:03:12,887 --> 00:03:15,408
And in VR, players are naturally even more critical

55
00:03:15,428 --> 00:03:16,388
of realistic characters,

56
00:03:16,768 --> 00:03:18,089
because we're essentially fooling them

57
00:03:18,129 --> 00:03:19,509
that we inhabit the same world,

58
00:03:20,069 --> 00:03:21,049
and there's no filter.

59
00:03:22,050 --> 00:03:23,730
Added to this, the higher frame rate

60
00:03:23,770 --> 00:03:25,051
we have to maintain for VR

61
00:03:25,371 --> 00:03:27,411
means we can't use the same game memory budgets

62
00:03:28,092 --> 00:03:30,212
reserved for regular console characters.

63
00:03:32,181 --> 00:03:35,487
But what if the solution actually lay in the advantages we have in VR?

64
00:03:36,108 --> 00:03:40,436
If we could create characters realistic and compelling enough to be believable and immerse

65
00:03:40,456 --> 00:03:43,662
the player through their interactions with them, they'd be less inclined to...

66
00:03:45,473 --> 00:03:50,079
And if we gave the player the starring role in the story and missions,

67
00:03:50,860 --> 00:03:52,582
so they were never a detached observer,

68
00:03:53,203 --> 00:03:55,546
again the focus would be on the unfolding drama

69
00:03:55,906 --> 00:03:58,970
rather than whether the eye shader or skin shader was absolutely perfect.

70
00:03:59,611 --> 00:04:03,135
With this approach we felt confident about exploring more realistic characters.

71
00:04:04,672 --> 00:04:07,433
Now the second rule, players don't allow their avatar

72
00:04:07,453 --> 00:04:08,593
to depict someone else.

73
00:04:09,213 --> 00:04:11,734
The theory being that a VR experience will be spoiled

74
00:04:11,834 --> 00:04:14,496
if a human avatar is a different gender or race to yourself.

75
00:04:15,176 --> 00:04:17,237
To avoid this, there should be no determiner

76
00:04:17,597 --> 00:04:19,498
of race or gender visible on the avatars.

77
00:04:21,078 --> 00:04:22,599
This is why the player wore leather gloves

78
00:04:22,619 --> 00:04:23,619
throughout the London heist,

79
00:04:23,899 --> 00:04:25,600
but we ended up with weird situations

80
00:04:25,640 --> 00:04:27,281
like sitting in a pub wearing leather gloves,

81
00:04:27,461 --> 00:04:29,061
which is a bit odd even on a cold day.

82
00:04:31,382 --> 00:04:32,203
Now this makes sense.

83
00:04:34,142 --> 00:04:36,502
If the premise of your game is you're meant to be you

84
00:04:36,582 --> 00:04:38,582
experiencing something amazing or magical,

85
00:04:39,062 --> 00:04:40,443
but for a game like Blood & Truth,

86
00:04:40,623 --> 00:04:42,903
where you're a James Bond, John Wick style hero,

87
00:04:43,263 --> 00:04:45,504
escapism and role-playing is the whole premise.

88
00:04:47,984 --> 00:04:49,624
Arkham VR, for example, is cool

89
00:04:49,644 --> 00:04:51,164
because you get to be Batman.

90
00:04:51,905 --> 00:04:53,225
I'd already mentioned giving the player

91
00:04:53,265 --> 00:04:54,725
the starring role to immerse them.

92
00:04:55,465 --> 00:04:58,726
Blood & Truth's key pillar is be the action hero.

93
00:04:59,086 --> 00:05:01,206
So we are very focused on convincing people

94
00:05:01,366 --> 00:05:03,447
they are this person and letting them revel in it.

95
00:05:06,052 --> 00:05:08,313
So it seemed natural to have the hands of our hero

96
00:05:08,373 --> 00:05:09,593
represented in the avatar.

97
00:05:10,054 --> 00:05:12,614
The most important thing for us was the player

98
00:05:12,674 --> 00:05:15,595
gets to feel they are Ryan Marks, SAS soldier,

99
00:05:15,976 --> 00:05:17,796
embroiled in London's criminal underworld.

100
00:05:22,158 --> 00:05:23,458
Scanning and photogrammetry.

101
00:05:24,378 --> 00:05:25,999
Making realistic game characters

102
00:05:26,379 --> 00:05:28,200
is challenging and time consuming.

103
00:05:28,540 --> 00:05:32,241
More and more developers are utilizing photogrammetry

104
00:05:32,281 --> 00:05:35,202
and 3D scanning to do this with impressive results.

105
00:05:36,738 --> 00:05:39,280
And when it came to making realistic characters of Blood and Truth,

106
00:05:39,561 --> 00:05:44,024
we thought it would be great to cast, costume, and scan real actors to play the key characters.

107
00:05:44,725 --> 00:05:48,828
Essentially create digital doubles and use these same actors for the mocap sessions.

108
00:05:50,009 --> 00:05:55,533
The game is set in modern day London, so we could easily cast suitable actors and buy appropriate costumes.

109
00:05:58,297 --> 00:06:02,720
As an initial test of Blood & Truth, we downloaded free photogrammetry humans from the web and

110
00:06:02,760 --> 00:06:06,063
reviewed them in the PSVR headset to see if they held up to scrutiny.

111
00:06:06,583 --> 00:06:12,767
This enabled us to see highly realistic characters in VR without spending months making full

112
00:06:12,787 --> 00:06:13,267
characters.

113
00:06:14,208 --> 00:06:15,989
They actually read really well, which was great.

114
00:06:18,191 --> 00:06:22,154
Problem was, we're a central London studio with limited space, so it was impossible to

115
00:06:22,194 --> 00:06:25,496
build and maintain a permanent photogrammetry capture stage on site.

116
00:06:27,063 --> 00:06:29,823
So we decided instead to look at handheld 3D scanners.

117
00:06:30,524 --> 00:06:32,244
These could be used straight out of the box.

118
00:06:33,064 --> 00:06:35,124
We'd simply book a meeting room with suitable lighting

119
00:06:35,204 --> 00:06:35,965
and get scanning.

120
00:06:38,345 --> 00:06:41,146
So I did some research and organized a demo at the studio

121
00:06:41,166 --> 00:06:42,106
with Artec scanners.

122
00:06:42,666 --> 00:06:44,686
The character team and I scanned a bunch of clothes

123
00:06:44,726 --> 00:06:46,427
and heads so we could assess the detail

124
00:06:46,807 --> 00:06:47,647
that we could capture.

125
00:06:49,687 --> 00:06:52,048
We also scanned some poses for clothing deformation.

126
00:06:53,621 --> 00:06:55,042
The results were really encouraging,

127
00:06:55,122 --> 00:06:56,783
so I did a pitch for our leadership team,

128
00:06:56,823 --> 00:06:59,125
and on the back of that we were able to buy an Artec Eva

129
00:06:59,385 --> 00:07:00,366
and a Spyder scanner.

130
00:07:04,789 --> 00:07:06,030
Now we moved into pre-production

131
00:07:06,050 --> 00:07:08,012
and began looking at R&D and workflow.

132
00:07:08,492 --> 00:07:11,274
We did some tests to simulate deformation on clothing.

133
00:07:11,675 --> 00:07:13,996
The idea was we'd scan people in various poses,

134
00:07:14,317 --> 00:07:15,718
capture the changes in folds,

135
00:07:15,798 --> 00:07:17,379
and use these in game to make the clothing

136
00:07:17,399 --> 00:07:18,200
look more realistic.

137
00:07:19,555 --> 00:07:21,136
Here's a video of the first test we made,

138
00:07:21,316 --> 00:07:24,457
using normal map blends and mesh blend shapes.

139
00:07:26,939 --> 00:07:28,439
So there's no cloth sim going on here,

140
00:07:28,479 --> 00:07:30,280
it's all blend shapes and normal map blending.

141
00:07:33,462 --> 00:07:34,422
The next step was to create

142
00:07:34,442 --> 00:07:35,963
a full benchmark character model.

143
00:07:36,543 --> 00:07:38,985
We scanned me in a suit, not for my dashing good looks,

144
00:07:39,105 --> 00:07:41,726
but it was a good test to see

145
00:07:41,766 --> 00:07:43,567
if we could create an accurate digital double.

146
00:07:44,837 --> 00:07:47,358
From this, we created a fully textured and rigged character.

147
00:07:47,778 --> 00:07:49,819
We reviewed it in the headset again, and it looked great,

148
00:07:49,839 --> 00:07:52,280
the first real validation of the process we were taking.

149
00:07:53,740 --> 00:07:56,181
It also served to define mesh and texture budgets

150
00:07:56,421 --> 00:07:58,782
and timings on how long these characters would take to make.

151
00:08:00,023 --> 00:08:01,804
Then I wrote a detailed production guide

152
00:08:02,204 --> 00:08:04,104
going through the workflow from start to finish.

153
00:08:05,145 --> 00:08:06,966
This guide was then adopted and added to

154
00:08:06,986 --> 00:08:09,046
by the character team, and we could send it out

155
00:08:09,066 --> 00:08:10,627
to Outsource as we brought them on board.

156
00:08:13,854 --> 00:08:16,998
Initially we planned to handle facial rigs and blend shapes in-house,

157
00:08:17,638 --> 00:08:20,361
and we worked with the animation and the rigging teams on initial tests.

158
00:08:21,342 --> 00:08:25,867
We were getting some really good results, but it soon became clear this was going to be a monumental task

159
00:08:25,907 --> 00:08:28,751
to get the level of quality we wanted for all our key characters.

160
00:08:29,511 --> 00:08:33,456
This led us to seek a third-party vendor who specialized in this field to partner with us.

161
00:08:35,718 --> 00:08:37,260
What the facial test did achieve though,

162
00:08:37,300 --> 00:08:39,504
was a good base head mesh and UVs,

163
00:08:40,105 --> 00:08:41,827
which was low poly enough for our budgets,

164
00:08:41,907 --> 00:08:43,450
but still looked really good in the headset.

165
00:08:44,211 --> 00:08:46,494
We could get a third party vendor to adopt this,

166
00:08:46,655 --> 00:08:49,760
for our, adopt this topology for all our key characters,

167
00:08:49,800 --> 00:08:50,981
sorry, for all our characters.

168
00:08:54,196 --> 00:08:55,057
Character tiers.

169
00:08:55,698 --> 00:08:57,741
Before production, we decided to split the character

170
00:08:57,761 --> 00:09:00,004
into two tiers based on their level of fidelity.

171
00:09:00,725 --> 00:09:03,489
Tier one was for key characters with speaking roles

172
00:09:03,509 --> 00:09:05,612
who the player would interact with in drama scenes.

173
00:09:06,413 --> 00:09:07,915
Tier two were for characters the player

174
00:09:07,935 --> 00:09:09,216
would encounter during missions.

175
00:09:10,158 --> 00:09:11,620
Let's talk about tier two first.

176
00:09:12,623 --> 00:09:16,005
These were mostly male NPCs split into different factions,

177
00:09:16,065 --> 00:09:19,526
such as the Street Gang and the Militia Fighters.

178
00:09:20,186 --> 00:09:23,007
Each faction had four to five gameplay classes within them

179
00:09:23,287 --> 00:09:24,947
with names like Heavy and Maniac.

180
00:09:26,028 --> 00:09:28,789
We received concept art to use as character look guides

181
00:09:29,209 --> 00:09:31,870
and briefs from design on the role of each gameplay cast,

182
00:09:32,370 --> 00:09:34,010
which also needed to inform their look.

183
00:09:34,870 --> 00:09:36,471
These are some of the Street Gang concepts.

184
00:09:36,791 --> 00:09:38,772
They occupy a derelict tower block in the game

185
00:09:38,792 --> 00:09:39,832
where you have to infiltrate

186
00:09:39,932 --> 00:09:42,033
and rescue one of the key characters.

187
00:09:44,197 --> 00:09:45,898
And this is the private security faction.

188
00:09:45,958 --> 00:09:48,559
These are highly trained soldiers you encounter later in the game.

189
00:09:53,362 --> 00:09:56,264
We decided the best way to get as much variety as possible

190
00:09:56,304 --> 00:09:58,505
was to create these characters using a modular system.

191
00:09:58,805 --> 00:10:01,607
So upper, lower bodies and heads and headgear and hair

192
00:10:01,707 --> 00:10:05,829
could be interchanged to create many NPCs from relatively few pieces.

193
00:10:08,391 --> 00:10:11,353
We hired a costume buyer to source clothing to match the concepts

194
00:10:11,573 --> 00:10:12,513
and use some of our own.

195
00:10:14,437 --> 00:10:15,937
You may notice this turn up later on.

196
00:10:19,159 --> 00:10:20,900
I sourced and purchased the military gear

197
00:10:20,920 --> 00:10:23,481
from various websites, mostly Airsoft ones.

198
00:10:24,902 --> 00:10:27,763
And I contacted companies such as Bates Footwear,

199
00:10:27,863 --> 00:10:30,984
Crye Precision, and Mechanics to license army boots,

200
00:10:31,405 --> 00:10:33,486
clothing, and gloves to add more authenticity

201
00:10:33,526 --> 00:10:34,866
to the private security faction.

202
00:10:35,487 --> 00:10:37,948
And we licensed this awesome Ronin ballistic helmet

203
00:10:37,968 --> 00:10:39,188
from DevTac in Japan.

204
00:10:41,249 --> 00:10:43,210
We also brought a full set of riot armor.

205
00:10:44,173 --> 00:10:48,117
I tried to order this from China originally, but I discovered I needed a government permit

206
00:10:48,137 --> 00:10:48,617
to do so.

207
00:10:48,637 --> 00:10:52,760
I was about to give up when I found a place in the UK that had a set for sale.

208
00:10:54,041 --> 00:10:54,682
It's very cool.

209
00:10:56,543 --> 00:10:59,245
All the tier 2 clothes were scanned in the studio with the Artex.

210
00:10:59,786 --> 00:11:03,608
They were adjusted to fit a single scan body to use as a kind of mannequin to dress with

211
00:11:03,628 --> 00:11:04,109
the scans.

212
00:11:06,190 --> 00:11:10,454
We processed the scans in Artex Studio and then in ZBrush we adjusted them to fit over

213
00:11:10,474 --> 00:11:11,575
the male body exactly.

214
00:11:12,773 --> 00:11:13,974
and then began cleaning them up.

215
00:11:14,294 --> 00:11:15,755
I could do an entire presentation

216
00:11:15,835 --> 00:11:17,996
on just scan clean-up best practices,

217
00:11:18,056 --> 00:11:19,397
but I won't bore you with that right now.

218
00:11:19,957 --> 00:11:21,618
With this method, we could use the same rig

219
00:11:21,638 --> 00:11:22,979
for all the Tier 2 characters.

220
00:11:23,839 --> 00:11:25,460
We also had a pool of female assets

221
00:11:25,500 --> 00:11:27,441
created as well for pets and civilians

222
00:11:27,642 --> 00:11:29,803
that also were fitted to a single body and rig.

223
00:11:32,463 --> 00:11:34,885
For the tier two heads, we scanned some of our team

224
00:11:34,905 --> 00:11:36,806
with the RTX, basically anybody we could find

225
00:11:36,846 --> 00:11:40,027
who looked intimidating, and we brought some scanned heads

226
00:11:40,107 --> 00:11:43,589
from the 1024 web store to add some further diversity.

227
00:11:44,770 --> 00:11:46,210
We ran these heads through our pipeline,

228
00:11:46,230 --> 00:11:48,692
so they all used our base head topology and UVs.

229
00:11:51,433 --> 00:11:54,675
We handled the facial rig for tier two characters in-house,

230
00:11:54,935 --> 00:11:56,796
because we only needed it to be fairly basic

231
00:11:56,896 --> 00:11:58,456
for barks and eye tracking.

232
00:12:00,189 --> 00:12:03,671
Here are some Maya grabs of some of the finished tier two modular parts.

233
00:12:04,031 --> 00:12:05,913
So this is a couple of the street gang upper bodies.

234
00:12:08,074 --> 00:12:12,157
And here's a couple of the private security pieces as well.

235
00:12:12,517 --> 00:12:16,860
We later added some accessories to the drop leg character on that guy so he could carry

236
00:12:16,900 --> 00:12:20,082
brass bags or shotgun bandoliers to add a bit more variety.

237
00:12:20,622 --> 00:12:22,683
Tier two characters came in between 30 and 40,000 tries.

238
00:12:26,540 --> 00:12:30,103
Our creative services department made logos and designs

239
00:12:30,183 --> 00:12:32,285
to add color and believability to the clothing

240
00:12:32,305 --> 00:12:33,345
of the tier two characters.

241
00:12:37,668 --> 00:12:38,489
Now, tier one.

242
00:12:38,749 --> 00:12:40,751
As I said before, tier one were key characters

243
00:12:40,791 --> 00:12:43,353
with speaking and dramatic scene roles.

244
00:12:44,413 --> 00:12:47,215
We received concept art and biography to use as guides.

245
00:12:48,236 --> 00:12:50,698
The next stage was auditioning and casting actors.

246
00:12:51,719 --> 00:12:53,300
Once cast, we got their measurements,

247
00:12:53,580 --> 00:12:55,521
brought costumes, and got them in for fittings.

248
00:12:57,152 --> 00:12:58,473
Unlike the tier two characters,

249
00:12:58,513 --> 00:13:00,474
they would be exact digital doubles,

250
00:13:00,574 --> 00:13:02,196
so their bodies and rigs were unique.

251
00:13:03,937 --> 00:13:05,518
