276
00:14:07,232 --> 00:14:08,412
in costume at the studio,

277
00:14:08,492 --> 00:14:10,433
but as we were taking them over to 3Lateral

278
00:14:10,453 --> 00:14:11,273
to do head scans,

279
00:14:11,353 --> 00:14:13,334
we decided to scan their clothing over there too.

280
00:14:14,114 --> 00:14:15,074
The main reason for this

281
00:14:15,154 --> 00:14:16,775
was for the clothing deformation scans

282
00:14:16,835 --> 00:14:17,795
I spoke about earlier.

283
00:14:18,770 --> 00:14:21,472
We'd scan actors in a rig pose that matches the base body

284
00:14:21,772 --> 00:14:24,354
and then a set of poses to capture clothing deformations

285
00:14:25,095 --> 00:14:28,557
for fold to then create fold and crease normal map

286
00:14:28,597 --> 00:14:29,858
blends and blend shapes.

287
00:14:30,779 --> 00:14:32,581
We decided on a small set of poses

288
00:14:33,141 --> 00:14:35,803
based on the most regular movements and deformations

289
00:14:35,843 --> 00:14:37,144
we were likely to see in the game.

290
00:14:38,165 --> 00:14:39,766
Some of these poses are hard to maintain

291
00:14:39,806 --> 00:14:41,367
while capturing with handheld scanners,

292
00:14:41,448 --> 00:14:43,869
so using three-lateralist photogrammetry's capture stage

293
00:14:43,990 --> 00:14:44,810
made a lot of sense.

294
00:14:47,268 --> 00:14:49,410
Let's talk about hair.

295
00:14:50,030 --> 00:14:52,412
Getting hair to look good in the headset is a challenge.

296
00:14:52,872 --> 00:14:55,734
Alpha is very expensive, and polycards can get very heavy

297
00:14:55,774 --> 00:14:56,515
geometry-wise.

298
00:14:57,555 --> 00:15:01,198
And the headset resolution can cause scintillation or shimmer

299
00:15:01,258 --> 00:15:03,239
on hair, which can be distracting to players.

300
00:15:04,340 --> 00:15:07,782
Luckily, tier two haircuts lend themselves to being non-alpha,

301
00:15:07,802 --> 00:15:09,523
as the hair was either gel-backed, partly

302
00:15:09,563 --> 00:15:10,784
shaved, or crew cut.

303
00:15:12,834 --> 00:15:16,437
For the Tier 1 hair, we created a wig mesh with no alpha on it

304
00:15:16,857 --> 00:15:18,479
that would define the big volumes of hair,

305
00:15:18,859 --> 00:15:20,560
and then we clad this with alpha cards.

306
00:15:21,201 --> 00:15:22,862
Again, James wrote some cool shaders

307
00:15:22,902 --> 00:15:24,463
that blend card intersections

308
00:15:24,784 --> 00:15:26,925
and would offset hair strands to simulate depth.

309
00:15:28,006 --> 00:15:30,388
He also worked with the graphics programmers on techniques

310
00:15:30,408 --> 00:15:32,510
to minimize any scintillation or shimmering.

